text: Color me skeptical about today’s agreement and I won’t vote for any promised solution until I see it written down. Given how we got here today, I just hope we do not find ourselves in the same place three weeks from now.
.@realDonaldTrump has proven to be an unreliable negotiating partner, even going back on his word with members of his own party.

However, no action was taken in the House to pass the bill. Further, @POTUS and his staff’s disrespectful and inflammatory rhetoric attacking both innocent children of immigrants and Democratic members of Congress does not lend itself to a constructive bipartisan deal.

While Senate Leadership made a verbal commitment for a vote, the House Speaker has not agreed to keep the promise made to DREAMers. Let’s not forget that the DREAM Act passed the Senate in 2013 as part of comprehensive immigration reform with strong bipartisan support.

Congressional Republicans have been too focused on passing irresponsible tax cuts - including today’s misguided delay of the medical device tax - to tackle critical issues like community health centers, disaster relief, and finding a permanent solution for DREAMers.
We cannot continue to threaten pay and benefits, critical services, and economic stability of fellow Americans because of dysfunction among members of the White House and Congress.

I want the federal government open for business, but today’s continuing resolution is only another short-term patch that does not solve the impasse. Congress must do its job and come to a long-term solution to keep our government open.

Q: Do furloughed federal employees get back pay after #TrumpShutdown?

That is up to the Congress and White House. The precedent has been that furloughed employees are later paid, through enactment of legislation. For example, that was done in the most recent shutdown in 2013.

Q: Which federal employees keep working during the #TrumpShutdown?

Federal agencies are required to classify their employees as either “essential” or “non-essential” during a shutdown, with “non-essential” employees (800,000 designated in 2013 shutdown) put on unpaid furlough.

Q: What is the impact of the #TrumpShutdown on food safety activities?

During shutdown, the FDA is unable to support the majority of its food safety activities. The 2013 shutdown sharply curtailed critical FDA food safety inspections of domestic & international food facilities.

Q: What is the impact on the Centers for Disease Control?

During shutdown, CDC has to greatly curtail its activities to conduct flu season surveillance & monitoring, promote immunization, support state & local health depts & update disease treatment & prevention recommendations.

Q: What is the impact on medical research?

During shutdown, NIH shuts down most medical research taking place, prevents the enrollment of patients in NIH Clinical Center studies, and stops reviewing medical research grant applications and making or renewing research grants.

Q: What is the impact on federal housing loans?

During shutdown, the Federal Housing Administration stops processing applications for housing loans. In 2013 shutdown, FHA delayed 500+ applications to develop, rehabilitate or refinance ~80,000 units of multifamily rental housing.

Q: What is the impact of the #TrumpShutdown on small businesses?

The shutdown halts federal loans to small businesses, stops review of applications for small businesses to obtain loans and loan guarantees (typically $1 billion/month).

Q: Will military personnel be paid?

@washingtonpost reports no gap in pay unless shutdown lasts past Feb. 1, and otherwise military continues working unpaid until shutdown ends or until Congress & @POTUS agree to cover their costs.

Q: What is the impact of the #TrumpShutdown on U.S. military personnel?

Defense Department issued guidance, saying, “Military personnel on active duty, including reserve component personnel on federal active duty, will continue to report for duty and carry out assigned duties.”

Q: What is the impact of the #TrumpShutdown on veterans’ services?

All VA medical facilities & clinics will remain fully operational. However, VA call centers & hotlines cease to function, and Veterans Benefits Administration public contact services are not available.

Q: How will the #TrumpShutdown affect FEMA clean-up efforts?

It’s unclear how ongoing FEMA recovery efforts (TX, FL, CA, PR & VI) will be impacted. FEMA staff would still respond to emergencies, but the administration has not clarified status of long-term projects.

Q: Will I still be able to visit the national parks during the #TrumpShutdown?

During the 2013 shutdown, national parks, monuments & the Smithsonian museums were closed. However, the administration announced it will work to keep parks “as accessible as possible” during shutdown.

Q: Will my mail still arrive during the #TrumpShutdown?

Yes. The approximately 500,000 Postal Service employees are exempt from furlough because the Postal Service is self-funded.

Q: Will I continue to receive my Social Security and SSI checks during the #TrumpShutdown?

During a government shutdown, recipients will continue to receive their Social Security and SSI checks. However, a shutdown suspends the issuance of Social Security cards.
